# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antigen
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The **adaptive immune system** (**AIS**), also known as the **acquired immune system** or **specific immune system**, is a subsystem of the immune system that is composed of specialized cells, organs, and processes that eliminate pathogens specifically.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune system is one of the two main immunity strategies found in vertebrates (the other being the innate immune system).
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Like the innate system, the adaptive immune system includes both humoral immunity components and cell-mediated immunity components and destroys invading pathogens.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Unlike the innate immune system, which is pre-programmed to react to common broad categories of pathogen, the adaptive immune system is highly specific to each particular pathogen the body has encountered.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Adaptive immunity creates immunological memory after an initial response to a specific pathogen, and leads to an enhanced response to future encounters with that pathogen.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies are a critical part of the adaptive immune system.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Adaptive immunity can provide long-lasting protection, sometimes for the person's entire lifetime.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] For example, someone who recovers from measles is now protected against measles for their lifetime; in other cases it does not provide lifetime protection, as with chickenpox.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] This process of adaptive immunity is the basis of vaccination.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The cells that carry out the adaptive immune response are white blood cells known as lymphocytes.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] B cells and T cells, two different types of lymphocytes, carry out the main activities: antibody responses, and cell-mediated immune response.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In antibody responses, B cells are activated to secrete antibodies, which are proteins also known as immunoglobulins.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies travel through the bloodstream and bind to the foreign antigen causing it to inactivate, which does not allow the antigen to bind to the host.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Antigens are any substances that elicit the adaptive immune response.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Sometimes the adaptive system is unable to distinguish harmful from harmless foreign molecules; the effects of this may be hayfever, asthma, or any other allergy.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In adaptive immunity, pathogen-specific receptors are "acquired" during the lifetime of the organism (whereas in innate immunity pathogen-specific receptors are already encoded in the genome).
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] This acquired response is called "adaptive" because it prepares the body's immune system for future challenges (though it can actually also be maladaptive when it results in allergies or autoimmunity).
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The system is highly adaptable because of two factors.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] First, somatic hypermutation is a process of accelerated random genetic mutations in the antibody-coding genes, which allows antibodies with novel specificity to be created.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Second, V(D)J recombination randomly selects one variable (V), one diversity (D), and one joining (J) region for genetic recombination and discards the rest, which produces a highly unique combination of antigen-receptor gene segments in each lymphocyte.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] This mechanism allows a small number of genetic segments to generate a vast number of different antigen receptors, which are then uniquely expressed on each individual lymphocyte.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Since the gene rearrangement leads to an irreversible change in the DNA of each cell, all progeny (offspring) of that cell inherit genes that encode the same receptor specificity, including the memory B cells and memory T cells that are the keys to long-lived specific immunity.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The term "adaptive" was first used by Robert Good in reference to antibody responses in frogs as a synonym for "acquired immune response" in 1964.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Good acknowledged he used the terms as synonyms but explained only that he preferred to use the term "adaptive".
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The term "adaptive" as used in immunology is problematic as acquired immune responses can be both adaptive and maladaptive in the physiological sense.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Indeed, both acquired and innate immune responses can be both adaptive and maladaptive in the evolutionary sense.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Most textbooks today, following the early use by Janeway, use "adaptive" almost exclusively and noting in glossaries that the term is synonymous with "acquired".
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The classic sense of "acquired immunity" came to mean, since Tonegawa's discovery, "antigen-specific immunity mediated by somatic gene rearrangements that create clone-defining antigen receptors".
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In the last decade, the term "adaptive" has been increasingly applied to another class of immune response not so-far associated with somatic gene rearrangements.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] These include expansion of natural killer (NK) cells with so-far unexplained specificity for antigens, expansion of NK cells expressing germ-line encoded receptors, and activation of other innate immune cells to an activated state that confers a short-term "immune memory".
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In this sense, "adaptive immunity" more closely resembles the concept of "activated state" or "heterostasis", thus returning in sense to the physiological sense of "adaptation" to environmental changes.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Acquired immunity is triggered in vertebrates when a pathogen evades the innate immune system and (1) generates a threshold level of antigen and (2) generates "stranger" or "danger" signals activating dendritic cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In humans, it takes 4–7 days for the adaptive immune system to mount a significant response.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] T and B lymphocytes are the cells of the adaptive immune system.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The human body has about 2 trillion lymphocytes, which are 20–40% of white blood cells; their total mass is about the same as the brain or liver.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The peripheral bloodstream contains only 2% of all circulating lymphocytes; the other 98% move within tissues and the lymphatic system, which includes the lymph nodes and spleen.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In humans, approximately 1–2% of the lymphocyte pool recirculates each hour to increase the opportunity for the cells to encounter the specific pathogen and antigen that they react to.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] B cells and T cells are derived from the same multipotent hematopoietic stem cells, and look identical to one another until after they are activated.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] B cells play a large role in the humoral immune response, whereas T cells are intimately involved in cell-mediated immune responses.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In all vertebrates except Agnatha, B cells and T cells are produced by stem cells in the bone marrow.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] T cell progenitors then migrate from the bone marrow to the thymus, where they develop further.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Acquired immunity relies on the capacity of immune cells to distinguish between the body's own cells and unwanted invaders.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The host's cells express "self" antigens.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] These antigens are different from those on the surface of bacteria or on the surface of virus-infected host cells ("non-self" or "foreign" antigens).
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune response is triggered by recognizing foreign antigen in the cellular context of an activated dendritic cell.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] With the exception of non-nucleated cells (including erythrocytes), all cells are capable of presenting antigen through the function of major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Some cells are specially equipped to present antigen, and to prime naive T cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Dendritic cells, B-cells, and macrophages are equipped with special "co-stimulatory" ligands recognized by co-stimulatory receptors on T cells, and are termed professional antigen-presenting cells (APCs).
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Several T cells subgroups can be activated by professional APCs, and each type of T cell is specially equipped to deal with each unique toxin or microbial pathogen.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The type of T cell activated, and the type of response generated, depends, in part, on the context in which the APC first encountered the antigen.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Dendritic cells engulf exogenous pathogens, such as bacteria, parasites or toxins in the tissues and then migrate, via chemotactic signals, to the T cell-enriched lymph nodes.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] During migration, dendritic cells undergo a process of maturation in which they lose most of their ability to engulf other pathogens, and develop an ability to communicate with T-cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The dendritic cell uses enzymes to chop the pathogen into smaller pieces, called antigens.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In the lymph node, the dendritic cell displays these non-self antigens on its surface by coupling them to a receptor called the major histocompatibility complex, or MHC (also known in humans as human leukocyte antigen (HLA)).
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] This MHC-antigen complex is recognized by T-cells passing through the lymph node.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Exogenous antigens are usually displayed on MHC class II molecules, which activate CD4+T helper cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Endogenous antigens are produced by intracellular bacteria and viruses replicating within a host cell.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The host cell uses enzymes to digest virally associated proteins and displays these pieces on its surface to T-cells by coupling them to MHC.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Endogenous antigens are typically displayed on MHC class I molecules, and activate CD8+ cytotoxic T-cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] With the exception of non-nucleated cells (including erythrocytes), MHC class I is expressed by all host cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Cytotoxic T cells (also known as TC, cytotoxic T-lymphocytes (CTLs), or killer T cells) are a sub-group of T cells that induce the death of cells that are infected with viruses (and other pathogens), or are otherwise damaged or dysfunctional.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Naive cytotoxic T cells are activated when their T-cell receptor (TCR) strongly interacts with a peptide-bound MHC class I molecule.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] This affinity depends on the type and orientation of the antigen/MHC complex, and is what keeps the CTL and infected cell bound together.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Once activated, the CTL undergoes a process called clonal selection, in which it gains functions and divides rapidly to produce an army of "armed" effector cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The activated CTL then travels throughout the body searching for cells that bear that unique MHC class I + peptide.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] When exposed to these infected or dysfunctional somatic cells, effector CTLs release perforin and granulysin: cytotoxins that form pores in the target cell's plasma membrane, allowing ions and water to flow into the infected cell and causing it to burst or lyse.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] CTLs release granzyme, a serine protease encapsulated in a granule that enters cells via pores to induce apoptosis (cell death).
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] To limit extensive tissue damage during an infection, CTL activation is tightly controlled and in general requires a very strong MHC/antigen activation signal, or additional activation signals provided by "helper" T-cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] On resolution of the infection, most effector cells die and phagocytes clear them away—but a few of these cells remain as memory cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] On a later encounter with the same antigen, these memory cells quickly differentiate into effector cells, dramatically shortening the time required to mount an effective response.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] CD4+ lymphocytes, also called "helper" T cells, are immune response mediators, and play an important role in establishing and maximizing the capabilities of the acquired immune response.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] These cells have no cytotoxic or phagocytic activity; and cannot kill infected cells or clear pathogens, but, in essence "manage" the immune response, by directing other cells to perform these tasks.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Helper T cells express T cell receptors (TCR) that recognize antigen bound to Class II MHC molecules.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The activation of a naive helper T-cell causes it to release cytokines, which influences the activity of many cell types, including the APC (Antigen-Presenting Cell) that activated it.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Helper T-cells require a much milder activation stimulus than cytotoxic T cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Helper T cells can provide extra signals that "help" activate cytotoxic cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Classically, two types of effector CD4+ T helper cell responses can be induced by a professional APC, designated Th1 and Th2, each designed to eliminate different types of pathogens.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The factors that dictate whether an infection triggers a Th1 or Th2 type response are not fully understood, but the response generated does play an important role in the clearance of different pathogens.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The Th1 response is characterized by the production of Interferon-gamma, which activates the bactericidal activities of macrophages, and induces B cells to make opsonizing (marking for phagocytosis) and complement-fixing antibodies, and leads to *cell-mediated immunity*.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In general, Th1 responses are more effective against intracellular pathogens (viruses and bacteria that are inside host cells).
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The Th2 response is characterized by the release of Interleukin 5, which induces eosinophils in the clearance of parasites.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Th2 also produce Interleukin 4, which facilitates B cell isotype switching.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In general, Th2 responses are more effective against extracellular bacteria, parasites including helminths and toxins.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Like cytotoxic T cells, most of the CD4+ helper cells die on resolution of infection, with a few remaining as CD4+ memory cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Increasingly, there is strong evidence from mouse and human-based scientific studies of a broader diversity in CD4+ effector T helper cell subsets.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Regulatory T (Treg) cells, have been identified as important negative regulators of adaptive immunity as they limit and suppress the immune system to control aberrant immune responses to self-antigens; an important mechanism in controlling the development of autoimmune diseases.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Follicular helper T (Tfh) cells are another distinct population of effector CD4+ T cells that develop from naive T cells post-antigen activation.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Tfh cells are specialized in helping B cell humoral immunity as they are uniquely capable of migrating to follicular B cells in secondary lymphoid organs and provide them positive paracrine signals to enable the generation and recall production of high-quality affinity-matured antibodies.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Similar to Tregs, Tfh cells also play a role in immunological tolerance as an abnormal expansion of Tfh cell numbers can lead to unrestricted autoreactive antibody production causing severe systemic autoimmune disorders.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The relevance of CD4+ T helper cells is highlighted during an HIV infection.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] HIV is able to subvert the immune system by specifically attacking the CD4+ T cells, precisely the cells that could drive the clearance of the virus, but also the cells that drive immunity against all other pathogens encountered during an organism's lifetime.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Gamma delta T cells (γδ T cells) possess an alternative T cell receptor (TCR) as opposed to CD4+ and CD8+ αβ T cells and share characteristics of helper T cells, cytotoxic T cells and natural killer cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Like other 'unconventional' T cell subsets bearing invariant TCRs, such as CD1d-restricted natural killer T cells, γδ T cells exhibit characteristics that place them at the border between innate and acquired immunity.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] On one hand, γδ T cells may be considered a component of adaptive immunity in that they rearrange TCR genes via V(D)J recombination, which also produces junctional diversity, and develop a memory phenotype.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] On the other hand, however, the various subsets may also be considered part of the innate immune system where a restricted TCR or NK receptors may be used as a pattern recognition receptor.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] For example, according to this paradigm, large numbers of Vγ9/Vδ2 T cells respond within hours to common molecules produced by microbes, and highly restricted intraepithelial Vδ1 T cells respond to stressed epithelial cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] B Cells are the major cells involved in the creation of antibodies that circulate in blood plasma and lymph, known as humoral immunity.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies (also known as immunoglobulin, Ig), are large Y-shaped proteins used by the immune system to identify and neutralize foreign objects.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In mammals, there are five types of antibody: IgA, IgD, IgE, IgG, and IgM, differing in biological properties; each has evolved to handle different kinds of antigens.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Upon activation, B cells produce antibodies, each of which recognize a unique antigen, and neutralizing specific pathogens.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Like the T cell, B cells express a unique B cell receptor (BCR), in this case, a membrane-bound antibody molecule.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] All the BCR of any one clone of B cells recognizes and binds to only one particular antigen.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] A critical difference between B cells and T cells is how each cell "sees" an antigen.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] T cells recognize their cognate antigen in a processed form – as a peptide in the context of an MHC molecule, whereas B cells recognize antigens in their native form.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Once a B cell encounters its cognate (or specific) antigen (and receives additional signals from a helper T cell (predominately Th2 type)), it further differentiates into an effector cell, known as a plasma cell.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Plasma cells are short-lived cells (2–3 days) that secrete antibodies.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] These antibodies bind to antigens, making them easier targets for phagocytes, and trigger the complement cascade.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] About 10% of plasma cells survive to become long-lived antigen-specific memory B cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Already primed to produce specific antibodies, these cells can be called upon to respond quickly if the same pathogen re-infects the host, while the host experiences few, if any, symptoms.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Primitive jawless vertebrates, such as the lamprey and hagfish, have an adaptive immune system that shows 3 different cell lineages, each sharing a common origin with B cells, αβ T cells, and innate-like γΔ T cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Instead of the classical antibodies and T cell receptors, these animals possess a large array of molecules called variable lymphocyte receptors (VLRs for short) that, like the antigen receptors of jawed vertebrates, are produced from only a small number (one or two) of genes.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] These molecules are believed to bind pathogenic antigens in a similar way to antibodies, and with the same degree of specificity.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] For a long time it was thought that insects and other invertebrates possess only innate immune system.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] However, in recent years some of the basic hallmarks of adaptive immunity have been discovered in insects.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Those traits are immune memory and specificity.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Although the hallmarks are present the mechanisms are different from those in vertebrates.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Immune memory in insects was discovered through the phenomenon of priming.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] When insects are exposed to non-lethal dose or heat killed bacteria they are able to develop a memory of that infection that allows them to withstand otherwise lethal dose of the same bacteria they were exposed to before.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Unlike in vertebrates, insects do not possess cells specific for adaptive immunity.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Instead those mechanisms are mediated by hemocytes.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Hemocytes function similarly to phagocytes and after priming they are able to more effectively recognize and engulf the pathogen.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] It was also shown that it is possible to transfer the memory into offspring.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] For example, in honeybees if the queen is infected with bacteria then the newly born workers have enhanced abilities in fighting with the same bacteria.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Other experimental model based on red flour beetle also showed pathogen specific primed memory transfer into offspring from both mothers and fathers.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The most commonly accepted theory of this specificity is based on the *Dscam* gene.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The *Dscam* gene, which mediates phagocytosis in some insects, contains three variable Ig domains.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] These domains can be alternatively spliced, producing a large number of possible isoforms.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] It has been shown that after exposure to different pathogens, different isoforms of Dscam are produced, and that these isoforms associate and defend against bacteria in an isoform-specific manner.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Another mechanism that supports the specificity of insect immunity is RNA interference (RNAi).
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] RNAi is a form of antiviral immunity with high specificity.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] It has several different pathways that all end with the virus being unable to replicate.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] One of the pathways is siRNA in which long double stranded RNA is cut into pieces that serve as templates for protein complex Ago2-RISC that finds and degrades complementary RNA of the virus.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] MiRNA pathway in cytoplasm binds to Ago1-RISC complex and functions as a template for viral RNA degradation.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Last one is piRNA where small RNA binds to the Piwi protein family and controls transposones and other mobile elements.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Despite the research the exact mechanisms responsible for immune priming and specificity in insects are not well described.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] CRISPR has a lot of short repeated sequences.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] These sequences are part of an adaptive immune system for prokaryotes.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] It allows them to remember and counter the bacteriophages which prey on them.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] They work as a kind of acquired immune system for bacteria.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] When B cells and T cells are activated some become memory B cells and some memory T cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Throughout the lifetime of an animal these memory cells form a database of effective B and T lymphocytes.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Upon interaction with a previously encountered antigen, the appropriate memory cells are selected and activated.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In this manner, the second and subsequent exposures to an antigen produce a stronger and faster immune response.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] This is "adaptive" in the sense that the body's immune system prepares itself for future challenges, but is "maladaptive" of course if the receptors are autoimmune.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Immunological memory can be in the form of either *passive* short-term memory or *active* long-term memory.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Passive memory is usually short-term, lasting between a few days and several months.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Newborn infants have had no prior exposure to microbes and are particularly vulnerable to infection.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Several layers of passive protection are provided by the mother.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] *In utero*, maternal IgG is transported directly across the placenta, so that, at birth, human babies have high levels of antibodies, with the same range of antigen specificities as their mother.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Breast milk contains antibodies (mainly IgA) that are transferred to the gut of the infant, protecting against bacterial infections, until the newborn can synthesize its own antibodies.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] This is passive immunity because the fetus does not actually make any memory cells or antibodies: It only borrows them.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Short-term passive immunity can also be transferred artificially from one individual to another via antibody-rich serum.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In general, active immunity is long-term and can be acquired by infection followed by B cell and T cell activation, or artificially acquired by vaccines, in a process called immunization.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Historically, infectious disease has been the leading cause of death in the human population.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Over the last century, two important factors have been developed to combat their spread: sanitation and immunization.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Immunization (commonly referred to as vaccination) is the deliberate induction of an immune response, and represents the single most effective manipulation of the immune system that scientists have developed.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Immunizations are successful because they utilize the immune system's natural specificity as well as its inducibility.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The principle behind immunization is to introduce an antigen, derived from a disease-causing organism, that stimulates the immune system to develop protective immunity against that organism, but that does not itself cause the pathogenic effects of that organism.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] An antigen (short for *anti*body *gen*erator), is defined as any substance that binds to a specific antibody and elicits an adaptive immune response.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Most viral vaccines are based on live attenuated viruses, whereas many bacterial vaccines are based on acellular components of microorganisms, including harmless toxin components.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Many antigens derived from acellular vaccines do not strongly induce an adaptive response, and most bacterial vaccines require the addition of *adjuvants* that activate the antigen-presenting cells of the innate immune system to enhance immunogenicity.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Most large molecules, including virtually all proteins and many polysaccharides, can serve as antigens.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The parts of an antigen that interact with an antibody molecule or a lymphocyte receptor, are called epitopes, or antigenic determinants.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Most antigens contain a variety of epitopes and can stimulate the production of antibodies, specific T cell responses, or both.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] A very small proportion (less than 0.01%) of the total lymphocytes are able to bind to a particular antigen, which suggests that only a few cells respond to each antigen.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Even in the absence of antigen stimulation, a human can produce more than 1 trillion different antibody molecules.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Millions of genes would be required to store the genetic information that produces these receptors, but, the entire human genome contains fewer than 25,000 genes.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Myriad receptors are produced through a process known as clonal selection.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] According to the clonal selection theory, at birth, an animal randomly generates a vast diversity of lymphocytes (each bearing a unique antigen receptor) from information encoded in a small family of genes.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] To generate each unique antigen receptor, these genes have undergone a process called V(D)J recombination, or *combinatorial diversification*, in which one gene segment recombines with other gene segments to form a single unique gene.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] This assembly process generates the enormous diversity of receptors and antibodies, before the body ever encounters antigens, and enables the immune system to respond to an almost unlimited diversity of antigens.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Throughout an animal's lifetime, lymphocytes that can react against the antigens an animal actually encounters are selected for action—directed against anything that expresses that antigen.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The innate and acquired portions of the immune system work together, not in spite of each other.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired arm, B, and T cells could not function without the innate system input.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] T cells are useless without antigen-presenting cells to activate them, and B cells are disabled without T cell help.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] On the other hand, the innate system would likely be overrun with pathogens without the specialized action of the adaptive immune response.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The cornerstone of the immune system is the recognition of "self" versus "non-self".
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Therefore, the mechanisms that protect the human fetus (which is considered "non-self") from attack by the immune system, are particularly interesting.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Although no comprehensive explanation has emerged to explain this mysterious, and often repeated, lack of rejection, two classical reasons may explain how the fetus is tolerated.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The first is that the fetus occupies a portion of the body protected by a non-immunological barrier, the uterus, which the immune system does not routinely patrol.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The second is that the fetus itself may promote local immunosuppression in the mother, perhaps by a process of active nutrient depletion.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] A more modern explanation for this induction of tolerance is that specific glycoproteins expressed in the uterus during pregnancy suppress the uterine immune response (see eu-FEDS).
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] During pregnancy in viviparous mammals (all mammals except Monotremes), endogenous retroviruses (ERVs) are activated and produced in high quantities during the implantation of the embryo.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] They are currently known to possess immunosuppressive properties, suggesting a role in protecting the embryo from its mother's immune system.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The immunodepressive action was the initial normal behavior of the virus, similar to HIV.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The fusion proteins were a way to spread the infection to other cells by simply merging them with the infected one (HIV does this too).
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] It is believed that the ancestors of modern viviparous mammals evolved after an infection by this virus, enabling the fetus to survive the immune system of the mother.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The human genome project found several thousand ERVs classified into 24 families.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] This theory, which builds on the existing clonal selection hypothesis and since 1974 has been developed mainly by Niels Jerne and Geoffrey W.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Hoffmann, is seen as being relevant to the understanding of the HIV pathogenesis and the search for an HIV vaccine.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] One of the most interesting developments in biomedical science during the past few decades has been elucidation of mechanisms mediating innate immunity.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] One set of innate immune mechanisms is humoral, such as complement activation.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Another set comprises pattern recognition receptors such as toll-like receptors, which induce the production of interferons and other cytokines increasing resistance of cells such as monocytes to infections.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Cytokines produced during innate immune responses are among the activators of adaptive immune responses.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies exert additive or synergistic effects with mechanisms of innate immunity.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Unstable HbS clusters Band-3, a major integral red cell protein; antibodies recognize these clusters and accelerate their removal by phagocytic cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Clustered Band 3 proteins with attached antibodies activate complement, and complement C3 fragments are opsonins recognized by the CR1 complement receptor on phagocytic cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] A population study has shown that the protective effect of the sickle-cell trait against falciparum malaria involves the augmentation of acquired as well as innate immune responses to the malaria parasite, illustrating the expected transition from innate to acquired immunity.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Repeated malaria infections strengthen acquired immunity and broaden its effects against parasites expressing different surface antigens.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] By school age most children have developed efficacious adaptive immunity against malaria.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] These observations raise questions about mechanisms that favor the survival of most children in Africa while allowing some to develop potentially lethal infections.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In malaria, as in other infections, innate immune responses lead into, and stimulate, adaptive immune responses.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The genetic control of innate and acquired immunity is now a large and flourishing discipline.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Humoral and cell-mediated immune responses limit malaria parasite multiplication, and many cytokines contribute to the pathogenesis of malaria as well as to the resolution of infections.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune system evolved as an elaboration of the innate immune system.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Lymphoid cells can be identified in some pre-vertebrate deuterostomes (i.e., sea urchins).
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The amphioxus is a chordate like all vertebrates.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Its genome includes many building blocks of the adaptive immune system, but none of the true hallmarks such as somatic recombination.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] There is, however, considerable expansion in LRR genes and immunoglobulin-fold genes.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] There is high polymorphism among different individuals, an example of diversity in the innate immune system.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune system, which has been best-studied in mammals, originated in jawed fish approximately 500 million years ago.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Most of the molecules, cells, tissues, and associated mechanisms of this system of defense are found in cartilaginous fishes.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Lymphocyte receptors, Ig and TCR, are found in all jawed vertebrates.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The most ancient Ig class, IgM, is membrane-bound and then secreted upon stimulation of cartilaginous fish B cells.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Another isotype, shark IgW, is related to mammalian IgD.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] TCRs, both α/β and γ/δ, are found in jawed fish (cladistically including mammals).
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Most elements of the jawed fish system are in place thanks to the second round of whole-genome duplication (2R) that the jawed fish have undergone, providing an expanded repertoire of immune-related genes.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The immunoprotease genes involved in antigen processing and presentation as well as the class I and class II genes, are closely linked within the MHC of almost all studied species.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] These systems, along with RAG, were set in place quickly after 2R had happened.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The MHC region is paralogous to the Ig/TCR region.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Comparing paralogous regions allow for the reconstruction of a *primordial immune complex*.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The cartilaginous fish system does have one critical difference compared to the system of bony fish (including mammals): the gene segments that undergo V(D)J recombination in bony fish are not organized in huge clusters like they are in bony fish.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Instead, these parts are arranged as "miniclusters" and rearrangement by RAG is largely limited within these clusters.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] As a result, not as many combinations are available compared to bony fish.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The RAG transposon likely invaded a "UrIg2" immunoglobin gene, which had an unsplit VJ, in an ancestor of all extant jawed fish.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Splitting the V and J exons is adaptive, as it enables greater variation through changing the size of the CDR3 loop.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] This feature is inherited by all the descendants of UrIg2 such as Ig and TCR.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The jawless fish are vertebrates like the jawed fish, but belong on a different branch.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] In jawless fish, three subsets of lymphocytes use variable lymphocyte receptors (VLRs) for antigen binding.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The VLRs are derived from pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) of the innate immune system.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Diversity is generated by a cytosine deaminase-mediated rearrangement of LRR-based DNA segments.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] The functional dichotomy between two of the lymphocyte subsets parallels Ig and TCR molecules.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Immunity can be acquired either actively or passively.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Immunity is acquired actively when a person is exposed to foreign substances and the immune system responds.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Passive immunity is when antibodies are transferred from one host to another.
[src:antigen/adaptive-immune-system] Both actively acquired and passively acquired immunity can be obtained by natural or artificial means.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] In immunology, **affinity maturation** is the process by which TFH cell-activated B cells produce antibodies with increased affinity for antigen during the course of an immune response.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] With repeated exposures to the same antigen, a host will produce antibodies of successively greater affinities.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] A secondary response can elicit antibodies with several fold greater affinity than in a primary response.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] Affinity maturation primarily occurs on membrane immunoglobulin of germinal center B cells and as a direct result of somatic hypermutation (SHM) and selection by TFH cells.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] Clonal selection: B cells that have undergone SHM must compete for limiting growth resources, including the availability of antigen and paracrine signals from TFH cells.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] The follicular dendritic cells (FDCs) of the germinal centers present antigen to the B cells, and the B cell progeny with the highest affinities for antigen, having gained a competitive advantage, are favored for positive selection leading to their survival.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] Positive selection is based on steady cross-talk between TFH cells and their cognate antigen presenting GC B cell.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] Because a limited number of TFH cells reside in the germinal center, only highly competitive B cells stably conjugate with TFH cells and thus receive T cell-dependent survival signals.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] B cell progeny that have undergone SHM, but bind antigen with lower affinity will be out-competed, and be deleted.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] Over several rounds of selection, the resultant secreted antibodies produced will have effectively increased affinities for antigen.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] Like the natural prototype, the *in vitro* affinity maturation is based on the principles of mutation and selection.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] The *in vitro* affinity maturation has successfully been used to optimize antibodies, antibody fragments or other peptide molecules like antibody mimetics.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] Random mutations inside the CDRs are introduced using radiation, chemical mutagens or error-prone PCR.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] In addition, the genetic diversity can be increased by chain shuffling.
[src:antigen/affinity-maturation] Two or three rounds of mutation and selection using display methods like phage display usually results in antibody fragments with affinities in the low nanomolar range.
[src:antigen/allele] An **allele** is a variant of the sequence of nucleotides at a particular location, or locus, on a DNA molecule.
[src:antigen/allele] Alleles can differ at a single position through single-nucleotide polymorphisms, but they can also have insertions and deletions of up to several thousand base pairs.
[src:antigen/allele] Most alleles result in little or no change in the characteristics of an individual organism but sometimes different alleles can result in different observable phenotypic traits such as antibiotic resistance in bacteria, developmental mutations in fruit flies, and genetic diseases in humans.
[src:antigen/allele] Nearly all multicellular organisms have two sets of chromosomes at some point in their biological life cycle; that is, they are diploid.
[src:antigen/allele] For a given locus, if the two chromosomes contain the same allele, they, and the organism, are homozygous with respect to that allele.
[src:antigen/allele] If the alleles are different, they, and the organism, are heterozygous with respect to those alleles.
[src:antigen/allele] A notable example of this is Gregor Mendel's discovery that the white and purple flower colors in pea plants were the result of a single gene with two alleles.
[src:antigen/allele] Mendel's discovery of what are now known as alleles resulted in three laws that help understand how alleles are passed on to progeny.
[src:antigen/allele] Popular definitions of 'allele' typically refer only to different alleles within genes.
[src:antigen/allele] For example, the ABO blood grouping is controlled by the ABO gene, which has six common alleles (variants).
[src:antigen/allele] In population genetics, nearly every living human's phenotype for the ABO gene is some combination of just these six alleles.
[src:antigen/allele] It derives from the Greek prefix ἀλληλο-, *allelo-*, meaning "mutual", "reciprocal", or "each other", which itself is related to the Greek adjective ἄλλος, *allos* (cognate with Latin *alius*), meaning "other".
[src:antigen/allele] In many cases, genotypic interactions between the two alleles at a locus can be described as dominant or recessive, according to which of the two homozygous phenotypes the heterozygote most resembles.
[src:antigen/allele] Where the heterozygote is indistinguishable from one of the homozygotes, the allele expressed is the one that leads to the "dominant" phenotype, and the other allele is said to be "recessive".
[src:antigen/allele] In the case of a heterozygote, the dominant allele will mask the effect of the recessive allele, giving a dominant phenotype.
[src:antigen/allele] The phenotype of recessive alleles are observable when an organism is homozygous recessive for a gene.
[src:antigen/allele] The degree and pattern of dominance varies among loci.
[src:antigen/allele] This type of interaction was first formally-described by Gregor Mendel.
[src:antigen/allele] However, many traits defy this simple categorization and the phenotypes are modelled by co-dominance and polygenic inheritance.
[src:antigen/allele] The term "wild type" allele is sometimes used to describe an allele that is thought to contribute to the typical phenotypic character as seen in "wild" populations of organisms, such as fruit flies (*Drosophila melanogaster*).
[src:antigen/allele] Such a "wild type" allele was historically regarded as leading to a dominant (overpowering – always expressed), common, and normal phenotype, in contrast to "mutant" alleles that lead to recessive, rare, and frequently deleterious phenotypes.
[src:antigen/allele] It is now appreciated that most or all gene loci are highly polymorphic, with multiple alleles, whose frequencies vary from population to population, and that a great deal of genetic variation is hidden in the form of alleles that do not produce obvious phenotypic differences.
[src:antigen/allele] Wild type alleles are often denoted by a superscript plus sign (*i.e.*, *p+* for an allele *p*).
[src:antigen/allele] A population or species of organisms typically includes multiple alleles at each locus among various individuals.
[src:antigen/allele] Allelic variation at a locus is measurable as the number of alleles (polymorphism) present, or the proportion of heterozygotes in the population.
[src:antigen/allele] A null allele is a gene variant that lacks the gene's normal function because it either is not expressed, or the expressed protein is inactive.
[src:antigen/allele] For example, at the gene locus for the ABO blood type carbohydrate antigens in humans, classical genetics recognizes three alleles, IA, IB, and i, which determine compatibility of blood transfusions.
[src:antigen/allele] (It is now known that each of the A, B, and O alleles is actually a class of multiple alleles with different DNA sequences that produce proteins with identical properties: more than 70 alleles are known at the ABO locus.
[src:antigen/allele] The frequency of alleles in a diploid population can be used to predict the frequencies of the corresponding genotypes (see Hardy–Weinberg principle).
[src:antigen/allele] where *p* is the frequency of one allele and *q* is the frequency of the alternative allele, which necessarily sum to unity.
[src:antigen/allele] Then, *p*2 is the fraction of the population homozygous for the first allele, 2*pq* is the fraction of heterozygotes, and *q*2 is the fraction homozygous for the alternative allele.
[src:antigen/allele] If the first allele is dominant to the second then the fraction of the population that will show the dominant phenotype is *p*2 + 2*pq*, and the fraction with the recessive phenotype is *q*2.
[src:antigen/allele] A number of genetic disorders are caused when an individual inherits two recessive alleles for a single-gene trait.
[src:antigen/allele] Recessive genetic disorders include albinism, cystic fibrosis, galactosemia, phenylketonuria (PKU), and Tay–Sachs disease.
[src:antigen/allele] Other disorders are also due to recessive alleles, but because the gene locus is located on the X chromosome, so that males have only one copy (that is, they are hemizygous), they are more frequent in males than in females.
[src:antigen/allele] Examples include red–green color blindness and fragile X syndrome.
[src:antigen/allele] Other disorders, such as Huntington's disease, occur when an individual inherits only one dominant allele.
[src:antigen/allele] While heritable traits are typically studied in terms of genetic alleles, epigenetic marks such as DNA methylation can be inherited at specific genomic regions in certain species, a process termed transgenerational epigenetic inheritance.
[src:antigen/allele] The term *epiallele* is used to distinguish these heritable marks from traditional alleles, which are defined by nucleotide sequence.
[src:antigen/allele] A specific class of epiallele, the metastable epialleles, has been discovered in mice and in humans which is characterized by stochastic (probabilistic) establishment of epigenetic state that can be mitotically inherited.
[src:antigen/allele] The term "idiomorph", from Greek 'morphos' (form) and 'idio' (singular, unique), was introduced in 1990 in place of "allele" to denote sequences at the same locus in different strains that have no sequence similarity and probably do not share a common phylogenetic relationship.
[src:antigen/allele] It is used mainly in the genetic research of mycology.
[src:antigen/allergen] An **allergen** is an otherwise harmless substance that triggers an allergic reaction in sensitive individuals by stimulating an immune response.
[src:antigen/allergen] In technical terms, an allergen is an antigen that is capable of stimulating a type-I hypersensitivity reaction in atopic individuals through immunoglobulin E (IgE) responses.
[src:antigen/allergen] Most humans mount significant immunoglobulin E responses only as a defense against parasitic infections.
[src:antigen/allergen] However, some individuals may respond to many common environmental antigens.
[src:antigen/allergen] In atopic individuals, non-parasitic antigens stimulate inappropriate IgE production, leading to type I hypersensitivity.
[src:antigen/allergen] Sensitivities vary widely from one person (or from one animal) to another.
[src:antigen/allergen] A very broad range of substances can be allergens to sensitive individuals.
[src:antigen/allergen] The World Health Organization and International Union of Immunological Societies (WHO/IUIS) Allergen Nomenclature Sub-Committee maintains a webpage listing every protein (as well as some carbohydrates) that have elicited a confirmed IgE reaction in humans.
[src:antigen/allergen] Allergens can be found in a variety of sources, such as dust mite excretion, Food allergies are not as common as food sensitivity, but some foods such as peanuts (a legume), nuts, seafood and shellfish are the cause of serious allergies in many people.
[src:antigen/allergen] The United States Food and Drug Administration recognizes nine foods as major food allergens: organic fats as well as sulfites (chemical-based, often found in flavors and colors in foods) at 10ppm and over.
[src:antigen/allergen] In other countries, due to differences in the genetic profiles of their citizens and different levels of exposure to specific foods, the official allergen lists will vary.
[src:antigen/allergen] Canada recognizes all nine of the allergens recognized by the US as well as mustard.
[src:antigen/allergen] The European Union additionally recognizes other organic grains .
[src:antigen/allergen] An allergic reaction can be caused by any form of direct contact with the allergen—consuming food or drink one is sensitive to (ingestion), breathing in pollen, perfume or pet dander (inhalation), or brushing a body part against an allergy-causing plant (direct contact).
[src:antigen/allergen] Other common causes of serious allergy are wasp, fire ant and bee stings, penicillin, and latex.
[src:antigen/allergen] An extremely serious form of an allergic reaction is called anaphylaxis.
[src:antigen/allergen] One form of treatment is the administration of sterile epinephrine to the person experiencing anaphylaxis, which suppresses the body's overreaction to the allergen, and allows for the patient to be transported to a medical facility.
[src:antigen/allergen] Substances that cause a non-IgE-mediated, non-type-I hypersensitivity reaction are also called "allergens" in a broad sense.
[src:antigen/allergen] In general, all contact dermatitides are type IV reactions, despite the name "allergic contact dermatitis".
[src:antigen/allergen] Various trees and wood products such as paper, cardboard, MDF etc. can also cause mild to severe allergy symptoms through touch or inhalation of sawdust such as asthma and skin rash.
[src:antigen/allergen] Seasonal allergy symptoms are commonly experienced during specific parts of the year, usually during spring, summer or fall when certain trees or grasses pollinate.
[src:antigen/allergen] This depends on the kind of tree or grass.
[src:antigen/allergen] For instance, some trees such as oak, elm, and maple pollinate in the spring, while grasses such as Bermuda, timothy and orchard pollinate in the summer.
[src:antigen/allergen] Grass allergy is generally linked to hay fever because their symptoms and causes are somehow similar to each other.
[src:antigen/allergen] Symptoms include rhinitis, which causes sneezing and a runny nose, as well as allergic conjunctivitis, which includes watering and itchy eyes.
[src:antigen/allergen] Also an initial tickle on the roof of the mouth or in the back of the throat may be experienced.
[src:antigen/allergen] Also, depending on the season, the symptoms may be more severe and people may experience coughing, wheezing, and irritability.
[src:antigen/allergen] A few people even become depressed, lose their appetite, or have problems sleeping.
[src:antigen/allergen] Moreover, since the sinuses may also become congested, some people experience headaches.
[src:antigen/allergen] If both parents have had allergies in the past, there is a 66% chance for the individual to experience seasonal allergies, and the risk lowers to 60% if just one parent has had allergies.
[src:antigen/allergen] The immune system also has strong influence on seasonal allergies, because it reacts differently to diverse allergens like pollen.
[src:antigen/allergen] When an allergen enters the body of an individual that is predisposed to allergies, it triggers an immune reaction and the production of antibodies.
[src:antigen/allergen] These allergen antibodies migrate to mast cells lining the nose, eyes, and lungs.
[src:antigen/allergen] When an allergen drifts into the nose more than once, mast cells release a slew of chemicals or histamines that irritate and inflame the moist membranes lining the nose and produce the symptoms of an allergic reaction: scratchy throat, itching, sneezing and watery eyes.
[src:antigen/allergen] Among seasonal allergies, there are some allergens that fuse together and produce a new type of allergy.
[src:antigen/allergen] For instance, grass pollen allergens cross-react with food allergy proteins in vegetables such as onion, lettuce, carrots, celery, and corn.
[src:antigen/allergen] Besides, the cousins of birch pollen allergens, like apples, grapes, peaches, celery, and apricots, produce severe itching in the ears and throat.
[src:antigen/allergen] The cypress pollen allergy brings a cross reactivity between diverse species like olive, privet, ash and Russian olive tree pollen allergens.
[src:antigen/allergen] In some rural areas, there is another form of seasonal grass allergy, combining airborne particles of pollen mixed with mold.
[src:antigen/allergen] Recent research has suggested that humans might develop allergies as a defense to fight off parasites.
[src:antigen/allergen] According to Yale University Immunologist Ruslan Medzhitov, protease allergens cleave the same sensor proteins that evolved to detect proteases produced by the parasitic worms.
[src:antigen/allergen] Additionally, a new report on seasonal allergies called "Extreme allergies and Global Warming", have found that many allergy triggers are worsening due to climate change.
[src:antigen/allergen] 16 states in the United States were named as "Allergen Hotspots" for large increases in allergenic tree pollen if global warming pollution keeps increasing.
[src:antigen/allergen] Therefore, researchers on this report claimed that global warming is bad news for millions of asthmatics in the United States whose asthma attacks are triggered by seasonal allergies.
[src:antigen/allergen] Seasonal allergies are one of the main triggers for asthma, along with colds or flu, cigarette smoke and exercise.
[src:antigen/allergen] In Canada, for example, up to 75% of asthmatics also have seasonal allergies.
[src:antigen/allergen] Based on the symptoms seen on the patient, the answers given in terms of symptom evaluation and a physical exam, doctors can make a diagnosis to identify if the patient has a seasonal allergy.
[src:antigen/allergen] After performing the diagnosis, the doctor is able to tell the main cause of the allergic reaction and recommend the treatment to follow.
[src:antigen/allergen] Two tests have to be done in order to determine the cause: a blood test and a skin test.
[src:antigen/allergen] Allergists do skin tests in one of two ways: either dropping some purified liquid of the allergen onto the skin and pricking the area with a small needle; or injecting a small amount of allergen under the skin.
[src:antigen/allergen] Alternative tools are available to identify seasonal allergies, such as laboratory tests, imaging tests, and nasal endoscopy.
[src:antigen/allergen] In the laboratory tests, the doctor will take a nasal smear and it will be examined microscopically for factors that may indicate a cause: increased numbers of eosinophils (white blood cells), which indicates an allergic condition.
[src:antigen/allergen] If there is a high count of eosinophils, an allergic condition might be present.
[src:antigen/allergen] Another laboratory test is the blood test for IgE (immunoglobulin production), such as the radioallergosorbent test (RAST) or the more recent enzyme allergosorbent tests (EAST), implemented to detect high levels of allergen-specific IgE in response to particular allergens.
[src:antigen/allergen] Although blood tests are less accurate than the skin tests, they can be performed on patients unable to undergo skin testing.
[src:antigen/allergen] Imaging tests can be useful to detect sinusitis in people who have chronic rhinitis, and they can work when other test results are ambiguous.
[src:antigen/allergen] There is also nasal endoscopy, wherein a tube is inserted through the nose with a small camera to view the passageways and examine any irregularities in the nose structure.
[src:antigen/allergen] Endoscopy can be used for some cases of chronic or unresponsive seasonal rhinitis.
[src:antigen/allergen] In 1952 basidiospores were described as being possible airborne allergens and were linked to asthma in 1969.
[src:antigen/allergen] Basidiospores are the dominant airborne fungal allergens.
[src:antigen/allergen] Fungal allergies are associated with seasonal asthma.
[src:antigen/allergen] They are considered to be a major source of airborne allergens.
[src:antigen/allergen] The basidiospore family include mushrooms, rusts, smuts, brackets, and puffballs.
[src:antigen/allergen] The airborne spores from mushrooms reach levels comparable to those of mold and pollens.
[src:antigen/allergen] The levels of mushroom respiratory allergy are as high as 30% of those with allergic disorder, but it is believed to be less than 1% of food allergies.
[src:antigen/allergen] Heavy rainfall (which increases fungal spore release) is associated with increased hospital admissions of children with asthma.
[src:antigen/allergen] A study in New Zealand found that 22 percent of patients with respiratory allergic disorders tested positive for basidiospores allergies.
[src:antigen/allergen] Mushroom spore allergies can cause either immediate allergic symptomatology or delayed allergic reactions.
[src:antigen/allergen] Those with asthma are more likely to have immediate allergic reactions and those with allergic rhinitis are more likely to have delayed allergic responses.
[src:antigen/allergen] A study found that 27% of patients were allergic to basidiomycete mycelia extracts and 32% were allergic to basidiospore extracts, thus demonstrating the high incidence of fungal sensitisation in individuals with suspected allergies.
[src:antigen/allergen] It has been found that out of basidiomycete caps, mycelia, and spore extracts, the spore extracts are the most reliable extract for diagnosing basidiomycete allergy.
[src:antigen/allergen] In Canada, 8% of children attending allergy clinics were found to be allergic to *Ganoderma*, a basidiospore.
[src:antigen/allergen] *Pleurotus ostreatus*, *Cladosporium*, and *Calvatia cyathiformis* are significant airborne spores.
[src:antigen/allergen] Other significant fungal allergens include *Aspergillus* and *Alternaria*-*Penicillium* families.
[src:antigen/allergen] In India, *Fomes pectinatus* is a predominant air-borne allergen affecting up to 22% of patients with respiratory allergies.
[src:antigen/allergen] Some fungal air-borne allergens such as *Coprinus comatus* are associated with worsening of eczematous skin lesions.
[src:antigen/allergen] Children who are born during Autumn months (during fungal spore season) are more likely to develop asthmatic symptoms later in life.
[src:antigen/allergen] Treatment includes over-the-counter medications, antihistamines, nasal decongestants, allergy shots, and alternative medicine.
[src:antigen/allergen] In the case of nasal symptoms, antihistamines are normally the first option.
[src:antigen/allergen] They may be taken together with pseudoephedrine to help relieve a stuffy nose and they can stop the itching and sneezing.
[src:antigen/allergen] Over-the-counter options include clemastine.
[src:antigen/allergen] However, these antihistamines may cause extreme drowsiness, therefore, people are advised to not operate heavy machinery or drive while taking this kind of medication.
[src:antigen/allergen] Other side effects include dry mouth, blurred vision, constipation, difficulty with urination, confusion, and lightheadedness.
[src:antigen/allergen] There is also a newer second generation of antihistamines that are generally classified as non-sedating antihistamines or anti-drowsy, which include cetirizine, loratadine, and fexofenadine.
[src:antigen/allergen] An example of nasal decongestants is pseudoephedrine and its side-effects include insomnia, restlessness, and difficulty urinating.
[src:antigen/allergen] Some other nasal sprays are available by prescription, including azelastine and ipratropium bromide.
[src:antigen/allergen] Some of their side-effects include drowsiness.
[src:antigen/allergen] For eye symptoms, it is important to first bathe the eyes with plain eyewash to reduce irritation.
[src:antigen/allergen] People should not wear contact lenses during episodes of conjunctivitis.
[src:antigen/allergen] Allergen immunotherapy treatment involves administering doses of allergens to accustom the body to induce specific long-term tolerance.
[src:antigen/allergen] Allergy immunotherapy can be administered orally (as sublingual tablets or sublingual drops), or by injections under the skin (subcutaneous).
[src:antigen/allergen] Immunotherapy contains a small amount of the substance that triggers the allergic reactions.
[src:antigen/allergen] Gradual introduction is also used for egg and milk allergies as a home-based therapy mainly for children.
[src:antigen/allergen] Such methods cited in the UK involve the gradual introduction of the allergen in a cooked form where the protein allergenicity has been reduced to become less potent.
[src:antigen/allergen] By reintroducing the allergen from a fully cooked, usually baked, state, research suggests that a tolerance can emerge to certain egg and milk allergies under the supervision of a dietitian or specialist.
[src:antigen/allergen] The suitability of this treatment is debated between British and North American experts.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] An **allergy** is an exaggerated immune response where the body mistakenly identifies an ordinarily harmless allergen as a threat.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergic reactions give rise to **allergic diseases** such as hay fever, allergic conjunctivitis, allergic asthma, atopic dermatitis, food allergies, and anaphylaxis.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Symptoms of allergic diseases may include red eyes, an itchy rash, sneezing, coughing, a runny nose, shortness of breath, or swelling.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Common allergens include pollen, certain foods, metals, insect stings, medications, and materials, such as latex.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The development of allergies is due to genetic and environmental factors.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The mechanism of allergic reactions involves immunoglobulin E antibodies (IgE) binding to an allergen and then to a receptor on mast cells or basophils, where they trigger the release of inflammatory chemicals such as histamine.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Diagnosis is typically based on a person's medical history.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Further testing of the skin or blood may be useful in certain cases.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Positive tests, however, may not necessarily mean there is a significant allergy to the substance in question.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Early exposure of children to potential allergens may be protective.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Treatments for allergies include avoidance of known allergens and the use of medications such as steroids and antihistamines.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] In severe reactions, injectable adrenaline (epinephrine) is recommended.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergen immunotherapy, which gradually exposes people to larger and larger amounts of allergen, is useful for some types of allergies such as hay fever and reactions to insect bites.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] In the developed world, about 20% of people are affected by allergic rhinitis, food allergy affects 10% of adults and 8% of children, and about 20% have or have had atopic dermatitis at some point in time.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Depending on the country, about 1–18% of people have asthma.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Anaphylaxis occurs in between 0.05–2% of people.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Rates of many allergic diseases appear to be increasing.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The word "allergy" was first used by Clemens von Pirquet in 1906.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Many allergens, such as dust or pollen, are airborne particles.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] In these cases, symptoms arise in areas exposed to air, such as the eyes, nose, and lungs.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] For instance, allergic rhinitis, also known as hay fever, irritates the nose, sneezing, itching, and redness of the eyes.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Inhaled allergens can also lead to increased production of mucus in the lungs, shortness of breath, coughing, and wheezing.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergic rhinitis can simultaneously occur with other allergic responses such as asthma.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Aside from these ambient allergens, allergic reactions can result from foods, insect stings, and reactions to medications like aspirin and antibiotics such as penicillin.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Symptoms of food allergy include abdominal pain, bloating, vomiting, diarrhea, itchy skin, and hives.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Food allergies rarely cause respiratory (asthmatic) reactions, or rhinitis.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Insect stings, food, antibiotics, and certain medicines may produce a systemic allergic response that is also called anaphylaxis; multiple organ systems can be affected, including the digestive system, the respiratory system, and the circulatory system.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Depending on the severity, anaphylaxis can include skin reactions, bronchoconstriction, swelling, low blood pressure, coma, and death.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] This type of reaction can be triggered suddenly or have a delayed onset.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The anaphylactic reaction may seem to subside, but may recur over time.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Substances that come into contact with the skin, such as latex, are also common causes of allergic reactions, known as contact dermatitis or eczema.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Skin allergies frequently cause rashes, or swelling and inflammation within the skin, in what is known as a "wheal and flare" reaction characteristic of hives and angioedema.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] With insect stings, a large local reaction may occur as an area of skin redness greater than 10 cm in size that can last one to two days.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] This reaction may also occur after immunotherapy.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The skin forms an effective barrier to the entry of most allergens, but this barrier cannot withstand everything.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] For example, an insect sting can breach the barrier and inject allergen into the affected spot.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] When an allergen enters the epidermis or dermis, it triggers a localized allergic reaction which activates the mast cells in the skin resulting in an immediate increase in permeability of blood vessels, leading to fluid leakage and swelling in the affected area.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Mast-cell activation also stimulates a skin lesion called the wheal-and-flare reaction.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Then the release of chemicals from local nerve endings by a nerve axon reflex causes the widening of surrounding cutaneous blood vessels, which causes redness of the surrounding skin.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] As part of the allergic response, the body has developed a secondary response that, in some individuals, causes a more widespread and sustained skin swelling.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] This usually occurs about 8 hours after the allergen originally comes in contact with the skin.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] When an allergen is ingested, a dispersed form of wheal-and-flare reaction, known as urticaria or hives, will appear when the allergen enters the bloodstream and eventually reaches the skin.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] This same skin reactivity allows allergists to test for existing allergies by injecting a small amount of an allergen into the skin, which causes a reaction at the injection site.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Even though these injections are very small and local, they still pose the risk of causing systemic anaphylaxis.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Substances that come into contact with the airways may trigger allergic reactions in the nose, sinuses, throat and lungs.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergic rhinitis, often referred to as hay fever, is one of the most common airway allergies and is characterized by sneezing, nasal congestion, rhinorrhea and itching of the nose and eyes.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Airborne allergens commonly associated with allergic rhinitis include pollen, house dust mites, animal dander and mold spores.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergic reactions involving the lower airways may contribute to allergic asthma, in which exposure to allergens can lead to bronchoconstriction, wheezing, coughing and shortness of breath.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Common triggers include pollen, dust mites, animal allergens and occupational exposures such as flour dust or chemical sensitizers.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Some allergic airway reactions may occur rapidly after exposure, while others develop over several hours.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Severe reactions involving airway swelling may impair breathing and constitute a medical emergency.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT) is responsible for distinguishing pathogenic organisms from harmless food proteins and commensal bacteria.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Antigens sampled across the intestinal epithelium are presented by CD103+ dendritic cells, which migrate to mesenteric lymph nodes and promote differentiation of Foxp3+ regulatory T cells (Tregs).
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] These Tregs subsequently return to the intestinal lamina propria, where cytokines such as interleukin-10 and transforming growth factor-β (TGF-β) contribute to the maintenance of immune tolerance and suppression of allergic T helper 2 (Th2) responses.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Disruption of these regulatory pathways may contribute to allergic sensitization and the development of food allergy.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Impairment of the intestinal epithelial barrier, altered antigen processing, inflammation, or reduced regulatory T-cell activity may shift immune responses toward IgE-mediated hypersensitivity.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Such defects in oral tolerance have been associated with increased Th2 polarization, elevated allergen-specific IgE production, and reduced regulatory immune activity.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Environmental and dietary factors, including vitamin D deficiency, infections, antibiotic exposure, and changes in food processing, may also influence allergy development through their effects on gut immunity and epithelial integrity.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The intestinal microbiome is increasingly recognized as an important factor in allergy development.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Early-life alterations in the composition and diversity of the intestinal microbiota have been associated with an increased risk of food allergy and atopic disease.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Commensal bacteria contribute to immune maturation, maintenance of epithelial barrier function, and induction of tolerogenic immune responses.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Reduced microbial diversity and loss of certain bacterial taxa may impair oral tolerance and promote allergic sensitization.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Short-chain fatty acids produced by intestinal bacteria may further support regulatory immune pathways and intestinal barrier integrity.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Sensitization to food allergens may also occur through non-oral routes.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Exposure to allergens through damaged skin, particularly in individuals with impaired skin barriers such as those with atopic dermatitis, may predispose to food allergy if oral tolerance has not yet been established.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] This has contributed to the hypothesis that the timing, route, and context of allergen exposure influence whether tolerance or allergic sensitization develops.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Research into gastrointestinal immune mechanisms has influenced preventive approaches to food allergy.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Early introduction of allergenic foods, including peanuts and eggs, during infancy has been associated in some populations with a reduced risk of food allergy, likely by promoting oral tolerance during critical periods of immune development.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Risk factors for allergies can be placed in two broad categories: host and environmental factors.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Host factors include heredity, sex, race, and age, with heredity being by far the most significant.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] However, there has been a recent increase in the incidence of allergic disorders that cannot be explained by genetic factors alone.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Four major environmental candidates are alterations in exposure to infectious diseases during early childhood, environmental pollution, allergen levels, and dietary changes.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Dust mite allergy, also known as house dust allergy, is a sensitization and allergic reaction to the droppings of house dust mites.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The allergy is common and can trigger allergic reactions such as asthma, eczema, or itching.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The mite's gut contains potent digestive enzymes (notably peptidase 1) that persist in their faeces and are major inducers of allergic reactions such as wheezing.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The mite's exoskeleton can also contribute to allergic reactions.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Unlike scabies mites or skin follicle mites, house dust mites do not burrow under the skin and are not parasitic.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Dust mite-proof encasements to mattress, pillow, and duvet prevent chronic contact with allergens.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] A wide variety of foods can cause allergic reactions, but 90% of allergic responses to foods are caused by cow's milk, soy, eggs, wheat, peanuts, tree nuts, fish, and shellfish.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Other food allergies, affecting less than 1 person per 10,000 population, may be considered "rare".
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The most common food allergy in the US population is a sensitivity to crustacea.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Although peanut allergies are notorious for their severity, peanut allergies are not the most common food allergy in adults or children.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Other allergens may trigger severe or life-threatening reactions and are more common when combined with asthma.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Rates of allergies differ between adults and children.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Children can sometimes outgrow peanut allergies.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Egg allergies affect one to two percent of children but are outgrown by about two-thirds of children by the age of 5.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The sensitivity is usually to proteins in the white, rather than the yolk.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Milk-protein allergies—distinct from lactose intolerance—are most common in children.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Approximately 60% of milk-protein reactions are immunoglobulin E–mediated, with the remaining usually attributable to inflammation of the colon.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Some people are unable to tolerate milk from goats or sheep as well as from cows, and many are also unable to tolerate dairy products such as cheese.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Roughly 10% of children with a milk allergy will have a reaction to beef.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Lactose intolerance, a common reaction to milk, is not a form of allergy at all, but due to the absence of an enzyme in the digestive tract.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Those with tree nut allergies may be allergic to one or many tree nuts, including pecans, pistachios, and walnuts.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] In addition, seeds, including sesame seeds and poppy seeds, contain oils in which protein is present, which may elicit an allergic reaction.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergens can be transferred from one food to another through genetic engineering; however, genetic modification can also remove allergens.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Little research has been done on the natural variation of allergen concentrations in unmodified crops.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Latex can trigger an IgE-mediated cutaneous, respiratory, and systemic reaction.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The prevalence of latex allergy in the general population is believed to be less than one percent.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] In a hospital study, 1 in 800 surgical patients (0.125 percent) reported latex sensitivity, although the sensitivity among healthcare workers is higher, between seven and ten percent.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Researchers attribute this higher level to the exposure of healthcare workers to areas with significant airborne latex allergens, such as operating rooms, intensive-care units, and dental suites.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] These latex-rich environments may sensitize healthcare workers who regularly inhale allergenic proteins.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The most prevalent response to latex is allergic contact dermatitis, a delayed hypersensitivity reaction that manifests as dry, crusted lesions.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] This reaction usually lasts 48–96 hours.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Sweating or rubbing the area under the glove aggravates the lesions, possibly leading to ulcerations.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Anaphylactic reactions occur most often in sensitive patients who have been exposed to a surgeon's latex gloves during abdominal surgery, but other mucosal exposures, such as dental procedures, can also produce systemic reactions.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Latex and banana sensitivity may cross-react.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Furthermore, those with latex allergy may also have sensitivities to avocado, kiwifruit, and chestnut.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] These people often have perioral itching and local urticaria.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Only occasionally have these food-induced allergies induced systemic responses.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Researchers suspect that the cross-reactivity of latex with banana, avocado, kiwifruit, and chestnut occurs because latex proteins are structurally homologous with some other plant proteins.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] About 10% of people report that they are allergic to penicillin; however, of that 10%, 90% turn out not to be.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Serious allergies only occur in about 0.03%.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] One of the main sources of human allergies is insects.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Insect bites, stings, ingestion, and inhalation can trigger an insect allergy.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Another non-food protein reaction, urushiol-induced contact dermatitis, originates after contact with poison ivy, eastern poison oak, western poison oak, or poison sumac.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Urushiol, which is not itself a protein, acts as a hapten and chemically reacts with, binds to, and changes the shape of integral membrane proteins on exposed skin cells.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The immune system does not recognize the affected cells as normal parts of the body, causing a T-cell-mediated immune response.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Of these poisonous plants, sumac is the most virulent.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The resulting dermatological response to the reaction between urushiol and membrane proteins includes redness, swelling, papules, vesicles, blisters, and streaking.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Estimates vary on the fraction of the population that will have an immune system response.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Approximately 25% of the population will have a strong allergic response to urushiol.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] In general, approximately 80–90% of adults will develop a rash if they are exposed to 0.0050 mg (7.7×10−5 gr) of purified urushiol.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Some people are so sensitive that a molecular trace on the skin can initiate an allergic reaction.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergic diseases are strongly familial; identical twins are likely to have the same allergic diseases about 70% of the time; the same allergy occurs about 40% of the time in non-identical twins.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergic parents are more likely to have allergic children and those children's allergies are likely to be more severe than those in children of non-allergic parents.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Some allergies, however, are not consistent along genealogies; parents who are allergic to peanuts may have children who are allergic to ragweed.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The likelihood of developing allergies is inherited and related to an irregularity in the immune system, but the specific allergen is not.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The risk of allergic sensitization and the development of allergies varies with age, with young children most at risk.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Several studies have shown that IgE levels are highest in childhood and fall rapidly between the ages of 10 and 30 years.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The peak prevalence of hay fever is highest in children and young adults, and the incidence of asthma is highest in children under 10.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Ethnicity may play a role in some allergies; however, racial factors have been difficult to separate from environmental influences and changes due to migration.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] It has been suggested that different genetic loci are responsible for asthma, to be specific, in people of European, Hispanic, Asian, and African origins.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Some loci, such as PRDM2 and POU2AF1, showed pleiotropic effects linking allergic and autoimmune conditions, suggesting shared inflammatory pathways across epithelial tissues.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Within atopic airway disease specifically, the same review noted that IL-13—produced mainly by activated TH2 cells—is a key driver of eosinophilic airway inflammation and remodeling, acting partly through pathways independent of IgE and eosinophils.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergic diseases are caused by inappropriate immunological responses to harmless antigens driven by a TH2-mediated immune response.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Many bacteria and viruses elicit a TH1-mediated immune response, which down-regulates TH2 responses.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The first proposed mechanism of action of the hygiene hypothesis was that insufficient stimulation of the TH1 arm of the immune system leads to an overactive TH2 arm, which in turn leads to allergic disease.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] In other words, individuals living in too sterile an environment are not exposed to enough pathogens to keep the immune system busy.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Since our bodies evolved to deal with a certain level of such pathogens, when they are not exposed to this level, the immune system will attack harmless antigens.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Thus, normally benign microbial objects—like pollen—will trigger an immune response.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] It is used to explain the increase in allergic diseases that have been seen since industrialization, and the higher incidence of allergic diseases in more developed countries.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The hygiene hypothesis has now expanded to include exposure to symbiotic bacteria and parasites as important modulators of immune system development, along with infectious agents.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Epidemiological data support the hygiene hypothesis.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Longitudinal studies in the third world demonstrate an increase in immunological disorders as a country grows more affluent and, it is presumed, cleaner.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The use of antibiotics in the first year of life has been linked to asthma and other allergic diseases.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The use of antibacterial cleaning products has also been associated with a higher incidence of asthma, as has birth by caesarean section rather than vaginal birth.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Chronic stress can aggravate allergic conditions.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] This has been attributed to a T helper 2 (TH2)-predominant response driven by suppression of interleukin 12 by both the autonomic nervous system and the hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal axis.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Stress management in highly susceptible individuals may improve symptoms.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergic diseases are more common in industrialized countries than in countries that are more traditional or agricultural, and there is a higher rate of allergic disease in urban populations versus rural populations, although these differences are becoming less defined.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Historically, the trees planted in urban areas were predominantly male to prevent litter from seeds and fruits, but the high ratio of male trees causes high pollen counts, a phenomenon that horticulturist Tom Ogren has called "botanical sexism".
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Alterations in exposure to microorganisms is another plausible explanation, at present, for the increase in atopic allergy.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Endotoxin exposure reduces release of inflammatory cytokines such as TNF-α, IFNγ, interleukin-10, and interleukin-12 from white blood cells (leukocytes) that circulate in the blood.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Certain microbe-sensing proteins, known as Toll-like receptors, found on the surface of cells in the body, are also thought to be involved in these processes.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Parasitic worms and similar parasites are present in untreated drinking water in developing countries, and were present in the water of developed countries until the routine chlorination and purification of drinking water supplies.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Recent research has shown that some common parasites, such as intestinal worms (e.g., hookworms), secrete chemicals into the gut wall (and, hence, the bloodstream) that suppress the immune system and prevent the body from attacking the parasite.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] This gives rise to a new slant on the hygiene hypothesis theory—that co-evolution of humans and parasites has led to an immune system that functions correctly only in the presence of the parasites.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Without them, the immune system becomes unbalanced and oversensitive.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] In particular, research suggests that allergies may coincide with the delayed establishment of gut flora in infants.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] However, the research to support this theory is conflicting, with some studies performed in China and Ethiopia showing an increase in allergy in people infected with intestinal worms.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Clinical trials have been initiated to test the effectiveness of helminthic therapy with certain worms in treating some allergies.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] It may be that the term 'parasite' could turn out to be inappropriate, and in fact a hitherto unsuspected symbiosis is at work.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] These TH2 cells interact with other lymphocytes called B cells, whose role is the production of antibodies.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Coupled with signals provided by IL-4, this interaction stimulates the B cell to begin production of a large amount of a particular type of antibody known as IgE.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Secreted IgE circulates in the blood and binds to an IgE-specific receptor (a kind of Fc receptor called FcεRI) on the surface of other kinds of immune cells called mast cells and basophils, which are both involved in the acute inflammatory response.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] At this stage, the IgE-coated cells are sensitized to the allergen.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] If later exposure to the same allergen occurs, the allergen can bind to IgE molecules held on the surface of the mast cells or basophils.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Cross-linking of the IgE and Fc receptors occurs when more than one IgE-receptor complex interacts with the same allergenic molecule and activates the sensitized cell.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] This results in rhinorrhea, itchiness, dyspnea, and anaphylaxis.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Depending on the individual, allergen, and mode of introduction, the symptoms can be system-wide (classical anaphylaxis) or localized to specific body systems.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Asthma is localized to the respiratory system, and eczema is localized to the dermis.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] After the chemical mediators of the acute response subside, late-phase responses can often occur.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] This is due to the migration of other leukocytes such as neutrophils, lymphocytes, eosinophils, and macrophages to the initial site.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The reaction is usually seen 2–24 hours after the original reaction.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Cytokines from mast cells may play a role in the persistence of long-term effects.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Late-phase responses in asthma differ slightly from those seen in other allergic responses.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] They are still caused by the release of mediators from eosinophils and remain dependent on TH2 cell activity.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Although allergic contact dermatitis is termed an "allergic" reaction (which usually refers to type I hypersensitivity), its pathophysiology involves a reaction that more correctly corresponds to a type IV hypersensitivity reaction.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] In type IV hypersensitivity, there is activation of certain types of T cells (CD8+) that destroy target cells on contact, as well as activated macrophages that produce hydrolytic enzymes.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Effective management of allergic diseases relies on the ability to make an accurate diagnosis.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergy testing can help confirm or rule out allergies.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Correct diagnosis, counseling, and avoidance advice based on valid allergy test results reduce the incidence of symptoms and need for medications, and improve quality of life.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] To assess the presence of allergen-specific IgE antibodies, two different methods can be used: a skin prick test or an allergy blood test.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Both methods are recommended, and they have similar diagnostic value.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Skin prick tests and blood tests are equally cost-effective, and health economic evidence shows that both tests are cost-effective compared with no test.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Early and more accurate diagnoses save costs due to reduced consultations, referrals to secondary care, misdiagnosis, and emergency admissions.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergy undergoes dynamic changes over time.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Regular allergy testing of relevant allergens provides information on if and how patient management can be changed to improve health and quality of life.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Annual testing is often the practice for determining whether allergy to milk, egg, soy, and wheat have been outgrown, and the testing interval is extended to 2–3 years for allergy to peanut, tree nuts, fish, and crustacean shellfish.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Results of follow-up testing can guide decision-making regarding whether and when it is safe to introduce or re-introduce allergenic food into the diet.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Skin testing is also known as "puncture testing" and "prick testing" since it involves a series of tiny punctures or pricks being placed into the patient's skin.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Tiny amounts of suspected allergens and/or their extracts (*e.g.*, pollen, grass, mite proteins, peanut extract) are introduced to sites on the skin marked with pen or dye (the ink/dye should be carefully selected, lest it cause an allergic response itself).
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] A negative and positive control are also included for comparison (e.g., negative is saline or glycerin; positive is histamine).
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] A small plastic or metal device is used to puncture or prick the skin.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Sometimes, allergens are injected "intradermally" into the patient's skin, with a needle and syringe.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Common areas for testing include the inside of the forearm and the back.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] If the patient is allergic to the substance, then a visible inflammatory reaction will usually occur within 30 minutes.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] This response ranges from slight reddening of the skin to a full-blown hive (called "wheal and flare") in more sensitive patients, similar to a mosquito bite.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Interpretation of the results of the skin prick test is usually done by allergists on a severity scale, with +/− meaning borderline reactivity, and 4+ representing a large reaction.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Increasingly, allergists are measuring and recording the diameter of the wheal-and-flare reaction.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Interpretation by well-trained allergists is often guided by relevant literature.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] In general, a positive response is interpreted when the wheal of an antigen is ≥3 mm larger than the wheal of the negative control (e.g., saline or glycerin).
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Some patients may believe they have determined their own allergic sensitivity from observation.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] A skin test is much better than patient observation for allergy detection.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] If a serious life-threatening anaphylactic reaction has brought a patient in for evaluation, some allergists may prefer to perform an initial blood test before conducting a skin prick test.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Skin testing may also not be possible in patients with widespread skin disease or those who have taken antihistamine within the past several days.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Patch testing is a diagnostic method used to identify substances that cause allergic contact dermatitis through a delayed hypersensitivity reaction.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] During the procedure, small amounts of potential allergens are applied to the skin, usually on the back, using adhesive patches containing standardized allergen preparations.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The patches are typically left in place for 48 hours, after which the skin is examined for localized eczematous reactions.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Additional readings are commonly performed 72–96 hours after application because allergic contact reactions may develop slowly.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Unlike skin prick testing, which is used to diagnose immediate IgE-mediated allergies, patch testing evaluates delayed type IV hypersensitivity reactions mediated by T cells.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergy blood testing, typically measuring allergen-specific IgE, is a quick test that can be ordered by a qualified healthcare professional.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Unlike skin-prick testing, it is not affected by antihistamines and may be used when skin testing is impractical, such as in people with extensive eczema or other skin disease, in pregnancy, or when there is concern about provoking symptoms.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] It can be performed in adults and children, including infants, although results must be interpreted together with the clinical history because sensitisation does not always mean clinical allergy.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] An allergy blood test is available through most laboratories.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] A sample of the patient's blood is sent to a laboratory for analysis, and the results are sent back a few days later.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Multiple allergens can be detected with a single blood sample.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergy blood tests are very safe because the person is not exposed to any allergens during the testing procedure.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] After the onset of anaphylaxis or a severe allergic reaction, guidelines recommend that emergency departments obtain a time-sensitive blood test to measure tryptase levels and assess for mast cells activation.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The test measures the concentration of specific IgE antibodies in the blood.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Quantitative IgE test results increase the possibility of ranking how different substances may affect symptoms.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] A rule of thumb is that the higher the IgE antibody value, the greater the likelihood of symptoms.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergens found at low levels that today do not result in symptoms cannot predict future symptom development.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The quantitative allergy blood result can help determine what a patient is allergic to, predict and monitor disease progression, estimate the risk of a severe reaction, and explain cross-reactivity.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] A low total IgE level is not adequate to rule out sensitization to commonly inhaled allergens.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Statistical methods, such as ROC curves, predictive value calculations, and likelihood ratios have been used to examine the relationship of various testing methods to each other.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] These methods have shown that patients with high total IgE have a high probability of allergic sensitization, but further investigation with allergy tests for specific IgE antibodies for a carefully chosen set of allergens is often warranted.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Laboratory methods to measure specific IgE antibodies for allergy testing include enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay, radioallergosorbent test, fluorescent enzyme immunoassay, and chemiluminescence immunoassay.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Before a diagnosis of allergic disease can be confirmed, other plausible causes of the presenting symptoms must be considered.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Vasomotor rhinitis, for example, is one of many illnesses that share symptoms with allergic rhinitis, underscoring the need for professional differential diagnosis.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Once a diagnosis of asthma, rhinitis, anaphylaxis, or other allergic disease has been made, there are several methods for discovering the causative agent of that allergy.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Giving peanut products early in childhood may decrease the risk of allergies, and only breastfeeding during at least the first few months of life may decrease the risk of allergic dermatitis.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] There is little evidence that a mother's diet during pregnancy or breastfeeding affects the risk of allergies, although there has been some research to show that irregular cow's milk exposure might increase the risk of cow's milk allergy.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] There is some evidence that delayed introduction of certain foods is useful, and that early exposure to potential allergens may actually be protective.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Following revisions to US and UK pediatric guidelines in 2015 and 2017 that encouraged introducing peanut products to high-risk infants at four to six months of age, one 2025 analysis found a 43% drop in the frequency of peanut allergies, with an estimated 40,000 cases prevented.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] According to that report, some pediatric experts have cautioned that real-world implementation of the guidelines may be inconsistent.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Fish oil supplementation during pregnancy is associated with a lower risk of food sensitivities.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Probiotic supplements during pregnancy or infancy may help to prevent atopic dermatitis.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Management of allergies typically involves avoiding the allergy trigger and taking medications to relieve symptoms.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergen immunotherapy may be useful for some types of allergies.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Several medications may be used to block the actions of allergic mediators, prevent cell activation, and degranulation processes.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] These include antihistamines, glucocorticoids, epinephrine (adrenaline), mast cell stabilizers, and antileukotriene agents are common treatments of allergic diseases.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Anticholinergics, decongestants, and other compounds thought to impair eosinophil chemotaxis are also commonly used.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Although rare, the severity of anaphylaxis often requires epinephrine injection, and where medical care is unavailable, a device known as an epinephrine autoinjector may be used.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Allergen immunotherapy is useful for environmental allergies, allergies to insect bites, and asthma.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Its benefit for food allergies is unclear and thus not recommended.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Immunotherapy involves exposing people to larger and larger amounts of allergen in an effort to change the immune system's response.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Meta-analyses have found that injections of allergens under the skin is effective in the treatment in allergic rhinitis in children and in asthma.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The benefits may last for years after treatment is stopped.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] It is generally safe and effective for allergic rhinitis and conjunctivitis, allergic forms of asthma, and stinging insects.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] To a lesser extent, the evidence also supports the use of sublingual immunotherapy for rhinitis and asthma.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] For seasonal allergies the benefit is small.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] In this form the allergen is given under the tongue and people often prefer it to injections.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Immunotherapy is not recommended as a stand-alone treatment for asthma.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] An experimental treatment, enzyme potentiated desensitization (EPD), has been tried for decades but is not generally accepted as effective.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] EPD uses dilutions of allergen and an enzyme, beta-glucuronidase, to which T-regulatory lymphocytes are supposed to respond by favoring desensitization, or down-regulation, rather than sensitization.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] EPD has also been tried for the treatment of autoimmune diseases, but evidence does not show effectiveness.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] A review found no effectiveness of homeopathic treatments and no difference compared with placebo.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The authors concluded that, based on rigorous clinical trials of all types of homeopathy for childhood and adolescent ailments, there is no convincing evidence that supports the use of homeopathic treatments.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The allergic diseases—hay fever and asthma—have increased in the Western world over the past 2–3 decades.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Increases in allergic asthma and other atopic disorders in industrialized nations, it is estimated, began in the 1960s and 1970s, with further increases occurring during the 1980s and 1990s, although some suggest that a steady rise in sensitization has been occurring since the 1920s.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The number of new cases per year of atopy in developing countries has, in general, remained much lower.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Although genetic factors govern susceptibility to atopic disease, increases in atopy have occurred within too short a period to be explained by a genetic change in the population, thus pointing to environmental or lifestyle changes.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Several hypotheses have been identified to explain this increased rate.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Increased exposure to perennial allergens may be due to housing changes and increased time spent indoors, and changes in cleanliness may decrease activation of a common immune control mechanisms or hygiene, and exacerbated by dietary changes, obesity, and decline in physical exercise.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The hygiene hypothesis maintains that high living standards and hygienic conditions expose children to fewer infections.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] It is thought that reduced bacterial and viral infections early in life direct the maturing immune system away from TH1 type responses, leading to unrestrained TH2 responses that allow for an increase in allergy.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Changes in rates and types of infection alone, however, have been unable to explain the observed increase in allergic disease, and recent evidence has focused attention on the importance of the gastrointestinal microbial environment.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] It is speculated that these infections exert their effect by critically altering TH1/TH2 regulation.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Important elements of newer hygiene hypotheses also include exposure to endotoxins, exposure to pets and growing up on a farm.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Some symptoms attributable to allergic diseases are mentioned in ancient sources.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Particularly, three members of the Roman Julio-Claudian dynasty (Augustus, Claudius and Britannicus) are suspected to have a family history of atopy.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The concept of "allergy" was originally introduced in 1906 by the Viennese pediatrician Clemens von Pirquet, after he noticed that patients who had received injections of horse serum or smallpox vaccine usually had quicker, more severe reactions to second injections.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Pirquet called this phenomenon "allergy" from the Ancient Greek words ἄλλος *allos* meaning "other" and ἔργον *ergon* meaning "work".
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] All forms of hypersensitivity were previously classified as allergies, and all were thought to be caused by an improper activation of the immune system.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Later, it became clear that several disease mechanisms were implicated, with a common link to disordered immune system activation.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] In 1963, a new classification scheme was designed by Philip Gell and Robin Coombs that described four types of hypersensitivity reactions, known as Type I to Type IV hypersensitivity.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] With this new classification, the word *allergy*, sometimes clarified as a *true allergy*, was restricted to type I hypersensitivities (also called immediate hypersensitivity), which are characterized as rapidly developing reactions involving IgE antibodies.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] A breakthrough in understanding the mechanisms of allergy was the discovery of the antibody class labeled immunoglobulin E (IgE).
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] IgE was simultaneously discovered in 1966–67 by two independent groups: Ishizaka's team at the Children's Asthma Research Institute and Hospital in Denver, USA, and by Gunnar Johansson and Hans Bennich in Uppsala, Sweden.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Their joint paper was published in April 1969.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] Radiometric assays include the radioallergosorbent test (RAST test) method, which uses IgE-binding (anti-IgE) antibodies labeled with radioactive isotopes for quantifying the levels of IgE antibody in the blood.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The RAST methodology was invented and marketed in 1974 by Pharmacia Diagnostics AB, Uppsala, Sweden, and the acronym RAST is actually a brand name.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] In 1989, Pharmacia Diagnostics AB replaced it with a superior test named the ImmunoCAP Specific IgE blood test, which uses the newer fluorescence-labeled technology.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p01] The updated version, the ImmunoCAP Specific IgE blood test, is the only specific IgE assay the Food and Drug Administration has approved to quantitatively report to its detection limit of 0.1 kU/L.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p02] The medical speciality that studies, diagnoses, and treats diseases caused by allergies is called allergology.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p02] An allergist is a physician specially trained to manage and treat allergies, asthma, and other allergic diseases.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p02] Becoming an allergist/immunologist requires completion of at least nine years of training.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p02] After completing medical school and graduating with a medical degree, a physician will undergo three years of training in internal medicine (to become an internist) or pediatrics (to become a pediatrician).
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p02] Internists or pediatricians wishing to focus on the sub-specialty of allergy-immunology then complete at least an additional two years of study, called a fellowship, in an allergy/immunology training program.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p02] Allergists/immunologists listed as ABAI-certified have successfully passed the certifying ABAI examination following their fellowship.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p02] In the United Kingdom, allergy is a subspecialty of general medicine or pediatrics.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p02] After obtaining postgraduate exams (MRCP or MRCPCH), a doctor works for several years as a specialist registrar before qualifying for the General Medical Council specialist register.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p02] Allergy services may also be delivered by immunologists.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p02] A 2003 Royal College of Physicians report presented a case for improvement of what were felt to be inadequate allergy services in the UK.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p02] In 2006, the House of Lords convened a subcommittee.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p02] It concluded likewise in 2007 that allergy services were insufficient to deal with what the Lords referred to as an "allergy epidemic" and its social cost; it made several recommendations.
[src:antigen/allergic-reaction-p02] Low-allergen foods are being developed, as are improvements in skin prick test predictions; evaluation of the atopy patch test, wasp sting outcomes predictions, a rapidly disintegrating epinephrine tablet, and anti-IL-5 for eosinophilic diseases.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Alloimmunity is caused by the difference between products of highly polymorphic genes, primarily genes of the major histocompatibility complex, of the donor and graft recipient.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] These products are recognized by T-lymphocytes and other mononuclear leukocytes which infiltrate the graft and damage it.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Blood transfusion can result in alloantibodies reacting towards the transfused cells, resulting in a transfusion reaction.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Even with standard blood compatibility testing, there is a risk of reaction against human blood group systems other than ABO and Rh.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Hemolytic disease of the fetus and newborn is similar to a transfusion reaction in that the mother's antibodies cannot tolerate the fetus's antigens, which happens when the immune tolerance of pregnancy is impaired.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] In many instances the maternal immune system attacks the fetal blood cells, resulting in fetal anemia.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Severe cases require intrauterine transfusions or early delivery to survive, while mild cases may only require phototherapy at birth.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Acute rejection is subsequent to the recipient's immune system identifies a graft organ as foreign.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] This results in the mounting of an immune response, leading to organ rejection and destruction.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Acute rejection is caused by antigen-specific Th1 and cytotoxic T-lymphocytes.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] They recognize transplanted tissue because of expression of alloantigens.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] When a genetic difference between the donor and recipient is detected, the immune system of the recipient identifies MHC I and MHC II as foreign.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Subsequently, CD4+ T-cells react to these alloantigens presented by antigen-presenting cells (APCs), resulting in the release of cytokines which stimulate immune reactivity.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] A transplant is rejected during first several days or weeks after transplantation.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Hyperacute and accelerated rejection is antibody-mediated immune response to the allograft.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] The difference between hyperacute and acute rejection lies in the presence of preformed antibodies that cause an instantaneous rejection.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Recipient's blood already contains circulating antibodies before the transplantation – either IgM or antibodies incurred by previous immunization (e.g. by repeated blood transfusion).
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] In case of hyperacute rejection, antibodies activate complement; moreover, the reaction can be enhanced by neutrophils.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] This type of rejection is very fast, the graft is rejected in a few minutes or hours after the transplantation.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Accelerated rejection leads to phagocyte and NK cell activation (not of the complement) through their Fc receptors that bind Fc parts of antibodies.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Graft rejection occurs within 3 to 5 days.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] This type of rejection is a typical response to xenotransplants.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Chronic rejection is not yet fully understood, but it is known that it is associated with alloantibody and cytokine production.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Endothelium of the blood vessels is being damaged, therefore the graft is not sufficiently supplied with blood and is replaced with fibrous tissue (fibrosis).
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] It takes two months at least to reject the graft in this way.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Unlimited graft acceptance is hindered by allogenic immune responses.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] CD4+ and CD8+ T-lymphocytes along with other mononuclear leukocytes (their exact function regarding the topic is not known) participate in the rejection.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] B-lymphocytes, NK cells and cytokines also play a role in it.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Humoral (antibody-mediated) type of rejection is caused by recipient's B-lymphocytes which produce alloantibodies against donor MHC class I and II molecules.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] These alloantibodies can activate the complement – this leads to target cell lysis.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Alternatively, donor cells are coated with alloantibodies that initiate phagocytosis through Fc receptors of mononuclear leukocytes.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] The mechanism of humoral rejection is relevant for hyperacute, accelerated and chronic rejection.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Alloimmunity can be also regulated by neonatal B cells.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] In addition to humoral immune responses, B-lymphocytes aid in T-cell activation by acting as antigen-presenting cells (APCs).
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] This is activation by indirect allorecognition is crucial, as these T-cells are able to translocate the follicular border to retrieve a T-follicular helper cell (Tfh).
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] This will then lead to an induced B-cellular response.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] They are important for lymphoid neogenesis (*de novo* formation of lymphoid tissues during transplant rejection) and forming in-graft tertiary lymphoid organs (TLOs).
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] TLOs also encourage a local alloimmune response needed for recovery and long-term health outcomes.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Cytokine microenvironment where CD4+ T-lymphocytes recognize alloantigens significantly influences polarization of the immune response.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] NK cells can also directly target the transplanted tissue.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] It depends on the balance of activating and inhibitory NK cell receptors and on their ligands expressed by the graft.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Receptors of KIR (Killer-cell immunoglobulin-like receptor) family bind concrete MHC class I molecules.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] If the graft has these ligands on its surface, NK cell cannot be activated (KIR receptors provide inhibitory signal).
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] So if these ligands are missing, there is no inhibitory signal and NK cell becomes activated.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] It recognizes target cells by "missing-self strategy" and induces their apoptosis by enzymes perforin and granzymes released from its cytotoxic granules.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Alloreactive NK cells also secrete proinflammatory cytokines IFN-γ and TNF-α to increase expression of MHC molecules and costimulatory receptors on the surface of APCs (antigen-presenting cells).
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] This promotes APC maturation which leads to amplification of T-cell alloreactivity by means of direct and also indirect pathway of alloantigen recognition (as described below).
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] NK cells are able to kill Foxp3+ regulatory T-lymphocytes as well and shift the immune response from graft tolerance toward its rejection.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Besides the ability of NK cells to influence APC maturation and T cell development, they can probably reduce or even prevent alloimmune response to transplanted tissue – either by killing the Donor APCs or by anti-inflammatory cytokine IL-10 and TGF-β secretion.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] NK cell sub-populations differ in alloreactivity rate and in their immunomodulatory potential.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Concerning immunosuppressive drugs, the effects on NK cells are milder in comparison to T cells.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Alloimmune response can be enhanced by proinflammatory cytokines and by CD4+ T-lymphocytes that are responsible for APC maturation and IL-2 production.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] IL-2 is crucial for **memory CD8+ T cell** development.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] These cells may represent a serious problem after the transplantation.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] As the effect of being exposed to various infections in the past, antigen-specific T-lymphocytes have developed in patient's body.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Part of them is kept in organism as memory cells and these cells could be a reason for "cross-reactivity" – immune response against unrelated but similar graft alloantigens.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] This immune response is called secondary and is faster, more efficient and more robust.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Transplanted tissue is accepted by immunocompetent recipient if it is functional in the absence of immunosuppressive drugs and without histologic signs of rejection.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Host can accept another graft from the same donor but reject graft from different donor.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Graft acceptance depends on the balance of proinflammatory Th1, Th17 lymphocytes and anti-inflammatory regulatory T cells.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Immunosuppressive drugs are used to suppress the immune response, but the effect is not specific.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Therefore, organism can be affected by the infection much more easily.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] The goal of the future therapies is to suppress the alloimmune response specifically to prevent these risks.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] The tolerance could be achieved by elimination of most or all alloreactive T cells and by influencing alloreactive effector-regulatory T-lymphocytes ratio in favor of regulatory cells which could inhibit alloreactive effector cells.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Another method would be based on costimulatory signal blockade during alloreactive T-lymphocytes activation.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Although alloimmunization is not a common phenomenon, roughly 2% among prenatal women, lack of proper care has been shown to result in complications during pregnancy, mortality, and significant morbidity.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Most often, pregnant women are susceptible to Red Blood Cell (RBC) alloimmunization.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] RBC alloimmunization is a result of exposure to non-self antigens, ranging from events like fetomaternal hemorrhage during pregnancy or blood and organ transfusions, among a plethora of different circumstances.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Historically, inaccessibility of proper care prior pregnancy and gaps in prevention strategies have affected certain groups of pregnant women more than others.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] There is evidence that, in the United States, insufficient care among racial and ethnic minorities are at higher risk of having severe alloimmunization that requires intrauterine transfusions (IUTs).
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] For example, roughly 18.6% of the IUT cohort were non-English speakers compared to 4.6% of maternal alloimmunization cases.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] This demonstrates the need for research in alloimmunity, especially amongst prenatal women, as well as accounting for adequate prenatal care for women of racial/ethnic minorities in the United States.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] For example, ensuring pregnant women receive Rho(D) immune globulin (RhIG) during pregnancy is crucial to reduce the risk of maternal alloimmunization.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Another risk factor that has been identified is the presence of anti-D antibodies in pregnant women.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Over half the women who suffer from maternal alloimmunization have anti-D antibodies which require anti-D prophylaxis and RhIG for treatment.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Furthermore, the risk of alloimmunization was higher in women within the Rhesus D-negative blood group, histories of blood transfusion, and poor obstetric history.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Other risk factors have been identified, such as an instance of fetomaternal hemorrhage (FMH; a relatively common occurrence in pregnancy), RBC and maternal genetics, as well as previous transfusions.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Additionally, mothers who are expecting and have sickle-cell disorder or thalassemia are often more likely to come across complications with alloimmunity due to frequent transfusions.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Transfusions expose these individuals, often of racial and ethnic minorities where these conditions are more prevalent, to many antigens from donors that results in alloimmunization.
[src:antigen/alloimmunity] Identifying these risks early in pregnancies and screening more thoroughly prevents instances of hemolytic disease of the fetus and newborn (HDFN) as well as protect the mother's longterm health.
[src:antigen/antigen] In immunology, an **antigen** (**Ag**) is a molecule, or portion thereof, that can bind to a specific antibody or T-cell receptor.
[src:antigen/antigen] The presence of antigens in the body may trigger an immune response.
[src:antigen/antigen] Antigens can be proteins, peptides (amino acid chains), polysaccharides (chains of simple sugars), lipids, or nucleic acids.
[src:antigen/antigen] Antigens exist on normal cells, cancer cells, parasites, viruses, fungi, and bacteria.
[src:antigen/antigen] Antigens are recognized by antigen receptors, including antibodies and T-cell receptors.
[src:antigen/antigen] Diverse antigen receptors are made by cells of the immune system so that each cell has a specificity for a single antigen.
[src:antigen/antigen] Upon exposure to an antigen, only the lymphocytes that recognize that antigen are activated and expanded, a process known as clonal selection.
[src:antigen/antigen] In most cases, antibodies are *antigen-specific*, meaning that an antibody can only react to and bind one specific antigen; in some instances, however, antibodies may cross-react to bind more than one antigen.
[src:antigen/antigen] The reaction between an antigen and an antibody is called the antigen-antibody reaction.
[src:antigen/antigen] Antigen can originate either from within the body ("self-protein" or "self antigens") or from the external environment ("non-self").
[src:antigen/antigen] The immune system identifies and attacks "non-self" external antigens.
[src:antigen/antigen] Antibodies usually do not react with self-antigens due to negative selection of T cells in the thymus and B cells in the bone marrow.
[src:antigen/antigen] The diseases in which antibodies react with self antigens and damage the body's own cells are called autoimmune diseases.
[src:antigen/antigen] Vaccines are examples of antigens in an immunogenic form, which are intentionally administered to a recipient to induce the memory function of the adaptive immune system towards antigens of the pathogen invading that recipient.
[src:antigen/antigen] The vaccine for seasonal influenza is a common example.
[src:antigen/antigen] Paul Ehrlich coined the term *antibody* (German: *Antikörper*) in his side-chain theory at the end of the 19th century.
[src:antigen/antigen] In 1899, Ladislas Deutsch (László Detre) named the hypothetical substances halfway between bacterial constituents and antibodies "antigenic or immunogenic substances" (French: *substances immunogènes ou antigènes*).
[src:antigen/antigen] He originally believed those substances to be precursors of antibodies, just as a zymogen is a precursor of an enzyme.
[src:antigen/antigen] But, by 1903, he understood that an antigen induces the production of immune bodies (antibodies) and wrote that the word *antigen* is a contraction of antisomatogen (*Immunkörperbildner*).
[src:antigen/antigen] The *Oxford English Dictionary* indicates that the logical construction should be "anti(body)-gen".
[src:antigen/antigen] The term originally referred to a substance that acts as an antibody generator.
[src:antigen/antigen] Antigens can be proteins, polysaccharides, lipids, nucleic acids or other biomolecules.
[src:antigen/antigen] This includes parts (coats, capsules, cell walls, flagella, fimbriae, and toxins) of bacteria, viruses, and other microorganisms.
[src:antigen/antigen] Non-microbial non-self antigens can include pollen, egg white, and proteins from transplanted tissues and organs or on the surface of transfused blood cells.
[src:antigen/antigen] Antigen-presenting cells present antigens in the form of peptides on major histocompatibility complexes.
[src:antigen/antigen] All nucleated cells (i.e., all cells except for red blood cells) express MHC class I, which samples peptides from the cytosol, defaulting to presenting self-antigen (unless something foreign ends up in the cytosol or if the cell is capable of cross-presentation).
[src:antigen/antigen] Antigens originating from outside the cell make their way into the endomembrane system via processes like phagocytosis, endocytosis, or macropinocytosis and are loaded onto MHC class II molecules.
[src:antigen/antigen] In contrast to MHC class I, MHC class II is expressed on a limited subset of cells, the vast majority of which are immune cells (some epithelial cells at mucosal surfaces may also express MHC class II).
[src:antigen/antigen] Often, when people refer to antigen-presenting cells, they are actually referring to professional antigen-presenting cells.
[src:antigen/antigen] Professional antigen-presenting cells refer to B cells, dendritic cells, Langerhans cells, and macrophages, all of which express MHC class II and have the ability to activate naive T cells (other antigen-presenting cells cannot supply naive T cells with all the signals required for activation).
[src:antigen/antigen] The MHC locus is the most polymorphic region of the entire human genome, and it is responsible for the presentation of antigens to T cells.
[src:antigen/antigen] This extensive polymorphism provides population-level protection by increasing the likelihood that some individuals will mount effective immune responses against novel pathogens, thus helping to ensure species survival during epidemics.
[src:antigen/antigen] Cheetahs, for example, underwent a bottleneck event 10,000 years ago that greatly limited the diversity of their MHC locus and as a result, show increased susceptibility to infectious diseases, though this represents one of multiple factors affecting their conservation status.
[src:antigen/antigen] CD4 T cells (in general, helper T cells) are able to recognize MHC class II molecules using CD4, and their T-cell receptor recognizes the specific peptide-MHC complex sequence.
[src:antigen/antigen] In contrast, CD8 T cells (in general, killer T cells) are able to recognize MHC class I molecules through the α3 domain of MHC class I (it does not recognize β2 microglobulin).
[src:antigen/antigen] T cell receptors are, in general, highly specific to particular peptide-MHC complexes.
[src:antigen/antigen] Some peptide sequences can only be presented by a specific type of MHC protein because they require specific amino acid sequences within the binding groove to associate with them.
[src:antigen/antigen] These are known as MHC-restricted peptides.
[src:antigen/antigen] If an individual does not express the relevant MHC protein needed for a given MHC-restricted peptide, they will not be able to present that antigen to T cells.
[src:antigen/antigen] Because the T cell receptor cannot recognize anything not presented on an MHC, conventional (see next paragraph) T cells are not capable of responding to non-peptide antigens (lipids, carbohydrates, etc), except in the case of post-translational modifications to peptides that end up being presented.
[src:antigen/antigen] However, attaching the polysaccharide to a carrier protein (especially an immunogenic one, such as tetanus toxoid) enables B cells that recognize the polysaccharide to get help from T cells that recognize the carrier protein's peptides.
[src:antigen/antigen] These are known as conjugate vaccines or glycoconjugates.
[src:antigen/antigen] Moreover, the processing of an antigen by an antigen-presenting cell causes loss of the tertiary structure of the protein, meaning that T cells recognize linear epitopes only (the amino acids recognized have to be next to each other in the primary structure).
[src:antigen/antigen] There are also subsets of T cells known as unconventional T cells that may recognize non-peptide antigens, or peptides.
[src:antigen/antigen] Many of these subsets show predominantly innate, rather than adaptive, functions.
[src:antigen/antigen] Mucosa-associated invariant T cells (MAIT) cells recognize ligands presented by the MHC-related protein MR1, which presents metabolites of riboflavin, pyridoxine, and folates.
[src:antigen/antigen] NKT cells recognize glycolipid antigens presented on CD1d, most prominently α-galactosylceramide.
[src:antigen/antigen] At the molecular level, an antigen can be characterized by its ability to bind to an antibody's paratopes.
[src:antigen/antigen] Different antibodies have the potential to discriminate among specific epitopes present on the antigen surface.
